{{Property law}}
In [[property law]], '''alienation''' is the voluntary act of an owner of some [[property]] disposing of the property, while '''alienable''' is the capacity for a piece of property or a [[Property rights (economics)|property right]] to be sold or otherwise transferred from one party to another.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/alienable|title=Alienable|first=John C|last=Busby|date=23 September 2009|website=LII / Legal Information Institute}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/alienable|title=alienable - Definition of alienable in English by Oxford Dictionaries|website=Oxford Dictionaries - English}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thelawdictionary.org/alienable/|title=What is ALIENABLE? definition of ALIENABLE (Black's Law Dictionary)|date=4 November 2011|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thelawdictionary.org/alienation/|title=What is ALIENATION? definition of ALIENATION (Black's Law Dictionary)|date=4 November 2011|publisher=}}</ref> Most property is alienable, but some may be subject to [[restraints on alienation]]. In England under the [[Feudal land tenure in England|feudal system]], land was generally transferred by [[subinfeudation]] and alienation required licence from the [[overlord]]. Some objects are incapable of being regarded as property and are '''inalienable''', such as people and body parts.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}} [[Aboriginal title]] is one example of inalienability (save to [[the Crown]]) in [[common law]] jurisdictions. A similar concept is non-transferability, such as tickets. Rights commonly described as a [[licence]] or permit are generally only personal and are not [[assignment (law)|assignable]]. However, they are alienable in the sense that they can generally be [[Surrender (law)|surrender]]ed.

English common law traditionally protected freehold landowners from unsecured creditors. In 1732, the [[Parliament of Great Britain]] passed legislation entitled “The Act for the More Easy Recovery of Debts in His Majesty’s Plantations and Colonies in America”, which required all real property in [[British America]] to be treated as [[Personal property|chattel]] for debt collection purposes.  The legislation was reenacted by many statehouses after the [[American Revolution]], leading to the more commodified and transferable development of American property law.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Priest|first1=Claire|title=Creating an American Property Law: Alienability and Its Limits in American History|journal=[[Harvard Law Review]]|date=2006|volume=120|page=385|url=https://harvardlawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/priest.pdf|accessdate=31 October 2017}}</ref>

