'''Alluvion''', a word taken from [[Roman law]], is a legal term, describing the increase in the area of land without any act being taken by the owner. The typical cause is sediment ([[alluvium]]) deposited by a river. This changes the size of a piece of land (a process called [[accession (property law)|accession]]) and thus its value over time.<ref>{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Alluvion|volume=1|page=710}}</ref>
